Assignment 2: Rating Prediction on Amazon Beauty Reviews

Team Members: Bokyoung Son (Data Engineering), Hangyi Zhao (Baselines), Yujin Lee (Matrix Factorization), William Ayoade (Advanced Models)

Dataset: Amazon Reviews 2023 - All_Beauty Category

Section 1: Task Definition

Predictive Task

We aim to predict user ratings (1-5 stars) for beauty products on Amazon based on historical review data.

Evaluation Metrics

  • MSE (Mean Squared Error): Primary metric for rating prediction accuracy
  • RMSE (Root Mean Squared Error): Interpretable version in original rating scale
  • MAE (Mean Absolute Error): Average prediction error magnitude

Baselines for Comparison

  1. Global Mean: Predict average rating for all users/items
  2. User Mean: Predict based on user's average rating
  3. Item Mean: Predict based on item's average rating
  4. Bias Model: Combines global mean with user/item biases

Model Validation

  • Train/test split: 80/20 with random seed 42
  • Compare against baselines and prior work
  • Analyze prediction errors and model behavior

Section 2: Data Collection and Preprocessing

Data Source

Dataset: Amazon Reviews 2023 - All_Beauty category
Source: McAuley Lab (https://cseweb.ucsd.edu/~jmcauley/datasets.html)
Original size: 701,528 reviews

Preprocessing Steps

  1. Load raw data from JSONL format
  2. K-core filtering (min 2 reviews per user/item) to ensure data quality
  3. Train/test split (80/20) with stratification
  4. Create user/item ID mappings for matrix indexing

Final Dataset Statistics

After preprocessing:

  • Total reviews: 72,387
  • Train reviews: 57,909 (80%)
  • Test reviews: 14,478 (20%)
  • Unique users: 29,162
  • Unique items: 14,918
  • Sparsity: 99.9%
  • Rating distribution: Heavily skewed toward 5-star reviews (61.5%)

    print("\nPlease download the file manually:")
    print("1. Go to: https://huggingface.co/datasets/McAuley-Lab/Amazon-Reviews-2023/tree/main/raw/review_categories")
    print("2. Click on 'All_Beauty.jsonl'")

print(f"File size: {os.path.getsize(jsonl_file) / 1024 / 1024:.2f} MB")

# Configuration
USE_SAMPLE = True
MAX_REVIEWS = 700000

# Load JSONL file line by line
reviews = []

with open(jsonl_file, 'r', encoding='utf-8') as f:
    if USE_SAMPLE:
        print(f"  Sample mode: loading first {MAX_REVIEWS:,} reviews")
        pbar = tqdm(total=MAX_REVIEWS, desc="Loading reviews")

        for i, line in enumerate(f):
            if i >= MAX_REVIEWS:
                break
            try:
                review = json.loads(line)
                reviews.append(review)
                pbar.update(1)
            except json.JSONDecodeError as e:
                # print(e)
                continue

        pbar.close()
    else:
        print("Loading all reviews (this may take a while)...")
        for line in tqdm(f, desc="Loading reviews"):
            try:
                review = json.loads(line)
                reviews.append(review)
            except json.JSONDecodeError:
                continue

# Convert to DataFrame
df_raw = pd.DataFrame(reviews)

print(f"\n Loaded {len(df_raw):,} reviews")

# IMAGE PROCESSING(slow)
'''
Image data
We processes the "images" column, which contains string-encoded lists of image
metadata. First we clean and parse these strings to extract usable urls, which
we then download, pixelize and encode as vectors which can be used by our model.
'''


df = pd.read_csv("/data/processed/train.csv")
print(f"Loaded train.csv: {df.shape}")


IMG_SIZE = (32, 32)           # 32x32 pixel encoding (low for speed, can be increased)
TIMEOUT = 5                   # 5 second timeout per HTTP request
SAVE_IMAGES = False           # keeps raw downloaded images if needed

# helper functions for processing the image data
def parse_images_field(raw):
    """
    Images are stored as strings, we convert these strings into usable dictionaries
    """
    if not isinstance(raw, str):
        return []

    raw = raw.strip()
    if raw == "" or raw == "[]" or raw.lower() == "nan":
        return []

    # Remove wrapping
    if raw.startswith("'[") and raw.endswith("]'"):
        raw = raw[1:-1]

    # Insert commas between dicts:  } {  ->  }, {
    raw_fixed = re.sub(r"}\s*{", "}, {", raw)

    try:
        parsed = ast.literal_eval(raw_fixed)
        return parsed if isinstance(parsed, list) else []
    except Exception as e:
        # debugging for bad entries
        print("\n--- PARSE ERROR ---")
        print("RAW:", raw[:200])
        print("FIXED:", raw_fixed[:200])
        print("ERROR:", e)
        return []

def extract_first_url(images_list):
  """
  We have list of urls, extract best one.
  Order: large -> medium -> small
  """
  for obj in images_list:
      if not isinstance(obj, dict):
          continue
      url = obj.get("large_image_url") or obj.get("medium_image_url") or obj.get("small_image_url")
      if url is not None:
          return url
  return None

def download_and_vectorize(url):
  """
  Try and fetch image. Then pixelate, and flatten image as usable vector
  """
  try:
      resp = requests.get(url, timeout=TIMEOUT)
      img = Image.open(BytesIO(resp.content)).convert("RGB")
      img = img.resize(IMG_SIZE)
      vec = np.asarray(img).flatten() / 255.0
      return vec
  except Exception:
      return None

Loaded train.csv: (57909, 10)
In[58]:
item_to_vec = {}
success = 0
fail_parse = 0
fail_download = 0
rows_with_images = 0

print("\n=== BEGIN FULL IMAGE PREPROCESSING ===")
for idx, row in tqdm(df.iterrows(), total=len(df)):

    item = row["item_id"]
    raw = row["images"]

    parsed = parse_images_field(raw)
    if len(parsed) == 0:
        continue

    rows_with_images += 1
    url = extract_first_url(parsed)
    if url is None:
        fail_parse += 1
        continue

    # avoid re-downloading for same item
    if item in item_to_vec:
        continue

    vec = download_and_vectorize(url)
    if vec is None:
        fail_download += 1
        continue

    item_to_vec[item] = vec
    success += 1

# text processing
from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import TfidfVectorizer
from sklearn.decomposition import TruncatedSVD
# Load preprocessed data
train = pd.read_csv('/data/processed/train.csv')
test = pd.read_csv('/data/processed/test.csv')



def clean_text(text):
    if not isinstance(text, str):
        return ""
    text = text.lower()

    # remove HTML
    text = re.sub(r"<.*?>", " ", text)

    # remove URLs
    text = re.sub(r"http\S+", " ", text)

    return re.sub(r"\s+", " ", text).strip()
train["clean_text"] = train["text"].apply(clean_text)
test["clean_text"]  = test["text"].apply(clean_text)


'''
  We define a list of stopwords to ignore, as they are common and dont
  provide useful information to our model
'''
stopwords = [
    "the","a","an","and","or","but","if","then","when","while","so", "i","me",
    "my","we","us","our","you","your","he","she","it","they","them","their",
    "is","am","are","was","were","be","been","being", "do","does","did","doing",
    "have","has","had","having", "for","to","from","in","on","at","by","of",
    "with","as","about","into", "over","under","through", "item"
]






# We create unigram, bigram, and trigrams from the review text
tfidf = TfidfVectorizer(
    stop_words=stopwords,
    ngram_range=(1,3),
    max_features=25000,
    min_df=3
)

tfidf_matrix = tfidf.fit_transform(train["clean_text"])
print("TF-IDF shape:", tfidf_matrix.shape)



# we shrink our dimentionality to 128,
# which improves speed while still keeping meaning
svd_dim = 128
svd = TruncatedSVD(n_components=svd_dim)

train_text_embeds = svd.fit_transform(tfidf_matrix)



# We create a text vector embedding for each item, stored as an item:vector dict
item_text_vecs = {}
grouped = train.groupby("item_id")

for item_id, grp in tqdm(grouped, desc="Building per-item text vectors"):
    idxs = grp.index
    # average all review vectors for this item
    item_text_vecs[item_id] = train_text_embeds[idxs].mean(axis=0)



save_dir = "/data/processed/text_vectors"
os.makedirs(save_dir, exist_ok=True)

with open(f"{save_dir}/item_text_vecs.pkl", "wb") as f:
    pickle.dump(item_text_vecs, f)

with open(f"{save_dir}/tfidf_model.pkl", "wb") as f:
    pickle.dump(tfidf, f)

with open(f"{save_dir}/svd_model.pkl", "wb") as f:
    pickle.dump(svd, f)

print("\n=== TEXT VECTORS SAVED SUCCESSFULLY ===")
print("Directory:", save_dir)

    """
    Returns the 128-dim vector for item_id.

Exploratory Data Analysis

Key observations:

  • Rating skew: 61.5% of ratings are 5 stars, indicating positive bias
  • Cold start: Many users and items have very few reviews (median = 2)
  • Imbalanced distribution: This makes predicting low ratings challenging

Section 3: Modeling

Baseline Models (Person 2):

Model Architectures

We implement four baseline models:

  1. Global Mean Baseline

    • Prediction: $\hat{r} = \mu$ (global average)
    • Simplest baseline, ignores user/item differences

  2. User Mean Baseline

    • Prediction: $\hat{r}_{ui} = \frac{1}{|I_u|} \sum_{j \in I_u} r_{uj}$
    • Uses only user's average rating

  3. Item Mean Baseline

    • Prediction: $\hat{r}_{ui} = \frac{1}{|U_i|} \sum_{v \in U_i} r_{vi}$
    • Uses only item's average rating

  4. Bias Model (Best baseline)

    • Prediction: $\hat{r}_{ui} = \mu + \beta_u + \beta_i$
    • Combines global mean with user and item biases
    • Trained via coordinate descent with L2 regularization ($\lambda = 5$)

Implementation Details

  • All predictions clipped to [1.0, 5.0] range
  • Bias model trained for 20 iterations (converged at iteration 6)
  • Regularization prevents overfitting on sparse data

# Baseline 4: Bias Model
# Prepare data structures
ratingsPerUser = defaultdict(list)
ratingsPerItem = defaultdict(list)

for _, row in train.iterrows():
    u = row['user_id']
    i = row['item_id']
    r = row['rating']
    ratingsPerUser[u].append((i, r))
    ratingsPerItem[i].append((u, r))

# Initialize parameters
alpha = train['rating'].mean()
betaU = defaultdict(float)
betaI = defaultdict(float)
lamb = 5
max_iter = 20

# Training functions
def update_alpha(train, betaU, betaI):
    numer = sum(row['rating'] - (betaU.get(row['user_id'], 0) + betaI.get(row['item_id'], 0))
                for _, row in train.iterrows())
    return numer / len(train)

def update_betaU(ratingsPerUser, alpha, betaI, lamb):
    newBetaU = {}
    for u, items in ratingsPerUser.items():
        numer = sum(r - (alpha + betaI.get(i, 0)) for (i, r) in items)
        newBetaU[u] = numer / (lamb + len(items))
    return newBetaU

def update_betaI(ratingsPerItem, alpha, betaU, lamb):
    newBetaI = {}
    for i, users in ratingsPerItem.items():
        numer = sum(r - (alpha + betaU.get(u, 0)) for (u, r) in users)
        newBetaI[i] = numer / (lamb + len(users))
    return newBetaI

# Train bias model
for t in range(max_iter):
    alpha = update_alpha(train, betaU, betaI)
    betaU = update_betaU(ratingsPerUser, alpha, betaI, lamb)
    betaI = update_betaI(ratingsPerItem, alpha, betaU, lamb)

    if t < 5 or (t+1) % 5==0 or t == max_iter - 1:
        train_mse = np.mean([(row['rating'] - np.clip(alpha + betaU.get(row['user_id'], 0) +
                                                        betaI.get(row['item_id'], 0), 1, 5))**2
                             for _, row in train.iterrows()])
        print(f"  Iter {t+1}: alpha={alpha:.3f}, Train MSE={train_mse:.4f}")

# Evaluate on test set
bias_preds = [np.clip(alpha + betaU.get(row['user_id'], 0) + betaI.get(row['item_id'], 0), 1.0, 5.0)
              for _, row in test.iterrows()]
bias_mse = mean_squared_error(test['rating'], bias_preds)

print(f"\nBias Model Test Results:")
print(f"  Test MSE: {bias_mse:.4f}")
print(f"  Test RMSE: {np.sqrt(bias_mse):.4f}")

Matrix Factorization Models

Model Architecture

We implement matrix factorization with bias terms:

$$ \hat{r}_{ui} = \mu + \beta_u + \beta_i + \mathbf{p}_u^T \mathbf{q}_i + \lambda_{\text{text}} \mathbf{w}_{\text{text}}^T \mathbf{t}_i + \lambda_{\text{image}} \mathbf{w}_{\text{image}}^T \mathbf{v}_i $$

Where:

  • $\mu$: Global mean rating
  • $\beta_u$: User bias (user's deviation from mean)
  • $\beta_i$: Item bias (item's deviation from mean)
  • $\mathbf{p}_u \in \mathbb{R}^k$: User latent factor vector
  • $\mathbf{q}_i \in \mathbb{R}^k$: Item latent factor vector
  • $k$: Number of latent factors (dimensionality)
  • $\mathbf{t}_i \in \mathbb{R}^{d_t}$: Text embedding vector for item $i$
  • $\mathbf{v}_i \in \mathbb{R}^{d_v}$: Image embedding vector for item $i$
  • $\mathbf{w}_{\text{text}} \in \mathbb{R}^{d_t}$: Trained text projection vector
  • $\mathbf{w}_{\text{image}} \in \mathbb{R}^{d_v}$: Trained image projection vector
  • $\lambda_{\text{text}}, \lambda_{\text{image}}$: Weights to adjust the strength of each term
  • $d_t$: Text feature dimension
  • $d_v$: Image feature dimension

Training via SGD

\usepackage{mathrsfs}

Minimize regularized loss: $$ \mathscr{L} = \sum_{(u,i,r) \in \text{train}} \left( r - \hat{r}_{ui} \right)^2 + \lambda \left( \|\mathbf{p}_u\|^2 + \|\mathbf{q}_i\|^2 + \beta_u^2 + \beta_i^2 \right) + \lambda_f \left( \|\mathbf{w}_{\text{text}}\|^2 + \|\mathbf{w}_{\text{image}}\|^2 \right) $$

Update rules:

  • $\beta_u \leftarrow \beta_u + \eta(e_{ui} - \lambda \beta_u)$

  • $\beta_i \leftarrow \beta_i + \eta(e_{ui} - \lambda \beta_i)$

  • $\mathbf{p}_u \leftarrow \mathbf{p}_u + \eta(e_{ui} \mathbf{q}_i - \lambda \mathbf{p}_u)$

  • $\mathbf{q}_i \leftarrow \mathbf{q}_i + \eta(e_{ui} \mathbf{p}_u - \lambda \mathbf{q}_i)$

  • $\mathbf{w}_{\text{text}} \leftarrow \mathbf{w}_{\text{text}} + \eta \left( e_{ui}\mathbf{t}_i - \lambda_f \mathbf{w}_{\text{text}} \right)$

  • $\mathbf{w}_{\text{image}} \leftarrow \mathbf{w}_{\text{image}} + \eta \left( e_{ui}\mathbf{v}_i - \lambda_f \mathbf{w}_{\text{image}} \right)$

  • $\lambda_{\text{text}} \leftarrow \lambda_{\text{text}} + \eta e_{ui} (\mathbf{w}_{\text{text}}^T \mathbf{t}_i)$

  • $\lambda_{\text{image}} \leftarrow \lambda_{\text{image}} + \eta e_{ui} (\mathbf{w}_{\text{image}}^T \mathbf{v}_i)$

Where $e_{ui} = r_{ui} - \hat{r}_{ui}$ is the prediction error.

Hyperparameter Selection

Person 3's grid search (72 experiments):

  • $k \in \{10, 20, 50, 100\}$
  • $\eta \in \{0.001, 0.005, 0.01\}$
  • $\lambda \in \{0.001, 0.01, 0.1\}$
  • Epochs $\in \{5, 10\}$

Best configuration found:

  • $k = 100$ (larger embeddings capture more patterns)
  • $\eta = 0.01$ (stable learning rate)
  • $\lambda = 0.01$ (light regularization)
  • Epochs = 10

# ================================
#      MULTIMODAL MF TRAINING
# ================================

train_user_idxs = set(train["user_idx"].values)
train_item_idxs = set(train["item_idx"].values)

best_mse = float("inf")
best_params = None

for ep in range(1, epochs + 1):
    np.random.shuffle(train_data)
    sq_err_sum = 0.0

    for u_idx, i_idx, r in train_data:
        u = int(u_idx)
        i = int(i_idx)

        t_i = item_text_matrix[i]
        v_i = item_image_matrix[i]

        # Prediction
        mf_part   = np.dot(P[u], Q[i])
        text_part = lambda_text  * np.dot(w_text,  t_i)
        img_part  = lambda_image * np.dot(w_image, v_i)

        pred = alpha + bu[u] + bi[i] + mf_part + text_part + img_part
        pred = np.clip(pred, 1, 5)
        err = r - pred

        # Updtating bias, P, and Q acording to update rules
        #   +()
        #   +()

        bu[u] += lr * (err - reg * bu[u])
        bi[i] += lr * (err - reg * bi[i])

        #    + (err *    * )
        #    + (err *    * )
        Pu_old = P[u].copy()
        Qi_old = Q[i].copy()

        P[u] += lr * (err * Qi_old - reg * Pu_old)
        Q[i] += lr * (err * Pu_old - reg * Qi_old)

        # Updating weights according to update rules
        # text  text + (err *    * text)
        # image  image + (err *    * image)
        w_text += lr_feat * (lambda_text * err * t_i - reg_f * w_text)
        w_image += lr_feat * (lambda_image * err * v_i - reg_f * w_image)

        # text  text + *err*(text)
        # image  image + *err*(image)
        lambda_text  += lr_mix * err * np.dot(w_text,  t_i)
        lambda_image += lr_mix * err * np.dot(w_image, v_i)

        # Normalize to keep stable
        lambda_text  = np.clip(lambda_text, 0.0, 2.0) / 2
        lambda_image = np.clip(lambda_image, 0.0, 2.0) / 2

        # sum the error over iterations
        sq_err_sum += err ** 2

    train_mse = sq_err_sum / len(train_data)

    # Track best parameters
    if train_mse < best_mse:
        best_mse = train_mse
        best_params = (P.copy(), Q.copy(), bu.copy(), bi.copy(),
                       w_text.copy(), w_image.copy(),
                       lambda_text, lambda_image)

    print(f"Epoch {ep:02d} | Train MSE={train_mse:.4f}")

print("\nTraining complete.")

Section 4: Evaluation and Results

Evaluation Protocol

Metrics:

  • MSE (Mean Squared Error): Primary metric, penalizes large errors heavily
  • RMSE (Root Mean Squared Error): More interpretable, in rating scale units
  • MAE (Mean Absolute Error): Robust to outliers

Why MSE?

  • Standard for rating prediction tasks (Netflix Prize, etc.)
  • Emphasizes getting close predictions right
  • Allows comparison with prior work

Model Comparison

Baseline Performance:

  1. User/Item means fail due to sparsity (99.9%)
  2. Global mean provides reasonable starting point
  3. Bias model captures user preferences and item quality

Matrix Factorization:

  • Learns latent patterns in user-item interactions
  • Combines explicit biases with learned embeddings
  • Achieves competitive performance with proper regularization

Analysis

Challenges:

  • Extreme sparsity limits model expressiveness
  • Rating imbalance (61.5% are 5-star) creates prediction bias
  • Cold start users/items difficult to predict accurately

Why MF works:

  • Discovers hidden factors (e.g., product quality, user taste)
  • Shares information across similar users/items
  • Regularization prevents overfitting to sparse data

        + lambda_image_best * np.dot(w_image_best, v_i)
    )

    preds.append(np.clip(pred, 1.0, 5.0))
    true.append(r)

final_mse = mean_squared_error(true, preds)

# Compare to baseline bias model
improvement = (bias_mse - final_mse) / bias_mse * 100

print("~~~~~~~~~~MULTIMODAL Matrix Factorization~~~~~~~~~~")
print(f"Test MSE:        {final_mse:.6f}")
print(f"Bias Model MSE:  {bias_mse:.6f}")
print(f"Difference:      {final_mse-bias_mse:+.6f}")

if improvement > 0:
    print(f"Improvement:  {improvement:.2f}% better")
else:
    print(f"Change:       {abs(improvement):.2f}% {'worse' if improvement < 0 else 'same'}")

Key Findings

  1. Bias Model is strong baseline: MSE = 1.44, hard to beat on sparse data
  2. Matrix Factorization competitive: Achieves similar or better performance
  3. Sparsity is main challenge: 99.9% sparsity limits all models
  4. Rating imbalance matters: Models struggle with low ratings (1-2 stars)
  5. Regularization critical: Prevents overfitting, especially for sparse users/items

Future Work

  • Add side information: Product text, images, categories
  • Time dynamics: Capture temporal patterns in ratings
  • Deep learning: Neural collaborative filtering, attention mechanisms
  • Ensemble methods: Combine multiple models for robustness

Section 5: Related Work

Amazon Reviews Research

The Amazon Reviews dataset (McAuley et al.) has been extensively used for:

  • Rating prediction: Collaborative filtering, matrix factorization
  • Review analysis: Sentiment analysis, helpfulness prediction
  • Recommendation: Top-N item suggestion, personalized ranking

Prior Approaches to Rating Prediction

  1. Matrix Factorization (Koren et al., 2009)

    • Won Netflix Prize with RMSE 0.85 on movie ratings
    • Our implementation follows similar principles
    • Different domain (beauty products vs. movies)

  2. Bias Models (Koren, 2008)

    • Simple but effective baseline
    • Often competitive with complex models on sparse data
    • Our results confirm this (MSE = 1.44)

  3. Neural Collaborative Filtering (He et al., 2017)

    • Deep learning approach
    • Works better with dense data
    • May not help on 99.9% sparse data

Comparison to Prior Work

Our results (MSE 1.44) are reasonable given:

  • Extreme sparsity (99.9%) vs. typical 95-98%
  • Small dataset (10K reviews) vs. millions
  • Cold start problem (median 2 reviews per user)

Consistent findings:

  • Bias models effective on sparse data
  • Regularization prevents overfitting
  • Simple methods competitive with complex ones

References

  • McAuley et al. (2023). Amazon Reviews 2023 Dataset
  • Koren, Y. (2009). "Matrix Factorization Techniques for Recommender Systems"
  • Koren, Y. (2008). "Factorization Meets the Neighborhood"
  • He et al. (2017). "Neural Collaborative Filtering"

Conclusion

We successfully implemented and compared multiple rating prediction models on Amazon Beauty reviews:

Achievements:

    1. Processed 700K reviews 70K high-quality samples
    1. Implemented 4 baseline models (Global, User, Item, Bias)
    1. Developed Matrix Factorization with learned embeddings
    1. Achieved competitive performance (MSE 1.36)
    1. Analyzed model behavior and error patterns

Key Insights:

  • Sparsity is the main challenge for rating prediction
  • Simple bias models are strong baselines
  • Latent factor models discover hidden patterns
  • Regularization critical for sparse data
